image.altText: A graphic of a thermometer and the globe indicating rising heat

props.synopsis: As the world continues its spell of hottest months on record, leading climate scientists say there is a margin to the persistent heat which cannot be explained by the effects of known climate drivers and global warming.

title.children: 'Uncharted territory': The world's extreme heat can't be fully explained, and scientists are worried

image.altText: Bespectacled woman with brown hair and yellow top sitting standing in front of new smart power meter

props.synopsis: Economists love them. Regulators say they make the grid more efficient. But many Australians are finding out time-of-use tariffs mean sharply higher power prices.

title.children: Anger and despair as electricity customers shifted to 'punishing' tariffs

image.altText: Eva Lawler at an indoor press conference with flags in the background.

props.synopsis: The NT government announces the youth curfew in Alice Springs, initially ordered for two weeks, will be extended by six nights.

title.children: Youth curfew in Alice Springs will be extended by six nights

image.altText: A smiling young blonde woman with a drink in her hand sits in the sun.

props.synopsis: Lachlan Young, 21, has faced a packed courtroom in Ballarat. He is charged with the murder of 23-year-old Hannah McGuire, whose body was found in a burnt-out car last week.

title.children: Man accused of murdering Hannah McGuire faces court in Ballarat

image.altText: A woman smiling and taking a selfie

props.synopsis: The alleged murder of a woman whose body was found in a burnt-out car near Ballarat last week reignites calls to prevent violence against women and create a culture of respect and equality.

title.children: Anti-violence advocate labels alleged murder of 23-year-old Clunes woman Hannah McGuire a 'national tragedy'

image.altText: A transgender woman walks past photographs outside a court house.

props.synopsis: Social media platform Giggle for Girls is being sued by transgender woman Roxanne Tickle after her access to the women-only app was revoked. The app's owner has denied Ms Tickle is a woman.

title.children: Transgender woman sues women-only social media platform she was excluded from

image.altText: Photo of two mobile phones in people's hands

props.synopsis: Australians are on track for a government-issued digital ID. Most people seem relaxed, but it's the number one story on "alt social media".

title.children: Spooky theories on the big-bad-almost hack and an ugly window into the world of 'alt social media'

image.altText: Back of grey-haired woman's head at desk with computer screen and take-away coffee cup

props.synopsis: New analysis from KPMG shows how COVID has pushed more people over 55 back into the workforce, with the retirement age steadily increasing over the past 20 years.

title.children: The average retirement age is going up, and young people entering the workforce may be working until 70

image.altText: An X-ray printout showing a pelvis with two hips replaced.

props.synopsis: Smart people are getting caught out on private health insurance — so do they need to be more savvy, or does the system need to change?

title.children: Australians seeking hip replacements tripped up by health insurance fine print

image.altText: Anthony Albanese at a press conference.

props.synopsis: Australia's Prime Minister Anthony Albanese urges his Israeli counterpart to avoid a ground invasion of Rafah in southern Gaza, after Benjamin Netanyahu flagged a date had been set for the offensive.

title.children: Albanese urges Netanyahu to avoid Rafah invasion, questions why Gaza aid has taken so long

image.altText: A woman with long brown hair stares directly in to a camera with a Palestinian flag behind her.

props.synopsis: Longevity has been a hallmark of the pro-Palestinian movement with protests calling for a change in government policy held weekly since mid-October. The Jewish community and its supporters have also held regular vigils to remember those killed and taken hostage.

title.children: Six months on from the Hamas attack on Israel and war in Gaza, people in Australia are showing they haven't forgotten

image.altText: A young John Farnham with long hair, smiling and wearing a leather jacket.

props.synopsis: Australian singing superstar John Farnham has announced the release of his memoir. After being asked many times, Farnham says "it finally felt like the right time to sit down and tell my story".

title.children: John Farnham to break his silence about personal life in new memoir

image.altText: People are splashing in a pool built on the foreshore.

props.synopsis: Tanya Plibersek has announced she plans to reject an apartment and retail development on an "internationally important" wetland at Queensland's Moreton Bay.

title.children: Controversial development on 'internationally important' wetland tentatively rejected

image.altText: Billie Eilish floats underwater blowing bubbles in a full black, tartan wardrobe

props.synopsis: The young pop superstar has released details of her third studio album. But she's not too happy that the announce didn't go as planned…

title.children: Billie Eilish announces new album. But has the surprise already been spoiled?

image.altText: A close up of a sulphur-crested cockatoo sitting in a tree and eating something held in its claw

props.synopsis: A Tasmanian prisoner who abused a cockatoo and killed juvenile sparrows while behind bars could potentially face more jail time after he pleaded guilty to animal cruelty charges.

title.children: Cruelty to cockatoo, sparrows could land inmate more jail time

image.altText: A man and a woman stand on a beach with their arms around each other. They have grave expressions on their faces.

props.synopsis: Peter Correy was tricked into sending $450,000 to an Australian oil company. A financial crime expert warns criminals are exploiting weaknesses in Australia's regulatory system to get away with laundering.

title.children: How criminals scammed a NSW couple out of $450k and used an Australian company to launder the money

image.altText: A man and woman hugging in front of a for sale sign at a house

props.synopsis: The issue of housing affordability in Australia was once confined almost entirely to home ownership, but has now boiled over into the rental market. Is it even possible to unwind a property bubble that's been two decades in the making?

title.children: Will the housing affordability crisis eat us up?

image.altText: A middle-aged man with receding hair and beard, wearing a singlet and glasses.

props.synopsis: Aliyawar Yawari had been charged with two counts of indecently assaulting a female guest at an Adelaide motel, however the charges will no longer proceed.

title.children: Indecent assault charges withdrawn against former immigration detainee

image.altText: A middle-aged, uniformed policeman speaks to the media.

props.synopsis: Paramedics found the 38-year-old with serious head injuries at Raymond Terrace early this morning. He died at the scene. A 29-year-old man has been taken into custody.

title.children: Man armed with axe dies after confrontation with man wielding Razor scooter, police allege

image.altText: Customers stand near the entrance of a shoe store called Vern's in a modern shopping mall

props.synopsis: Police confiscate more than 1,100 shoes across Malaysia ahead of the end of Ramadan after an outcry over the footwear's logo that resembles the word "Allah" in Arabic script.

title.children: 'Design flaws': Malaysian shoes with logo resembling Arabic word for God seized during Ramadan

image.altText: Matildas coach Tony Gustavsson scratches his head while speaking to media at a press conference

props.synopsis: Tony Gustavsson is set to field a different looking Matildas outfit in this week's friendly against Mexico, as the team continues to deal with injuries to a host of big-name players ahead of the Olympics.

title.children: Gustavsson seeking 'answers' as injuries threaten to derail Olympic dream

image.altText: Ella Mason poses for a photo with a medicine ball on their shoulder, at Pony Club Gym in Melbourne.

props.synopsis: Building muscle isn't just for powerlifters and body builders. These experts explain how some resistance training, even just at home, can impact how we experience ageing.

title.children: This exercise has a huge effect on our health and longevity, but many of us ignore it

image.altText: A portrait photo of two Filipino Australian women standing beside each other, smiling, in the stands of a large stadium

props.synopsis: Taylor Swift's Love Story has become a popular song for proposals during her Eras Tour. The song is a loose retelling of Romeo and Juliet, which was especially fitting for this couple who became engaged during the Australian tour.

title.children: Marry me, Jules: The Taylor Swift-inspired love story

image.altText: A submarine with a red, white and blue flag on the front sits on an empty patch of concrete

props.synopsis: Australia and its AUKUS partners, the US and UK, are considering including Japan in some of the alliance's advanced technology projects, the three countries' defence ministers confirm.

title.children: China 'gravely concerned' as Australia, US, UK confirm Japan being considered for AUKUS

image.altText: A young man leans on the open door of a car.

props.synopsis: Conflict in the Middle East and Ukraine, improved economic conditions in the US and China and cuts to production have combined to drive the price of crude oil up. Converted to petrol and diesel, it's shipped to Australia, and the cost of it is only going one way: up.

title.children: Consumers feel the pinch as fuel set to get more expensive in the coming weeks and months

image.altText: Marles and a man in navy uniform stand in a courtyard, an Australian flag behind them.

props.synopsis: Vice-Admiral David Johnston will lead Australia's armed forces as chief of the defence force, pending the approval of the governor-general.

title.children: Vice-Admiral David Johnston named new chief of the defence force

image.altText: Two women look at a share price board outside the ASX in Sydney.

props.synopsis: The ASX is in positive territory, ahead of key US inflation data to be released on Wednesday. Follow the day's events and insights as they happen with our business reporters on the ABC News live markets blog.

title.children: ASX in positive territory, Ken Henry says Australia has 'colonial economic structure'

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Dominique Grubisa and DG Institute made misleading representations to students in wealth seminars
Consumer sentiment sinks back towards historic lows

image.altText: A girl with scabs and bruises on her forehead is hugged by a women in a black and white headscarf

props.synopsis: One Monday late last year I received a call from the Australian Red Cross: "What would you say about going to Gaza?" I didn't hesitate. Sometimes I wonder why I have no fear.

title.children: This is the reality of life under fire in Gaza as an international medical aid worker

image.altText: Benjamin Netanyahu wearing suit stands in front of flag of Israel

props.synopsis: Details of an agreement struck between Australia and Israel on defence industry cooperation will not be released publicly over concerns the information could damage Australia's "international relations".

title.children: Details of defence deal with Israel kept under wraps to protect Australia's 'reputation'

image.altText: A mechanical piece of equipment - an electrolyser - on display on a table.

props.synopsis: The Gladstone Electrolyser Facility in central Queensland will be the first facility in Australia to build electrolysers at a commercial scale.

title.children: What are hydrogen electrolysers and can they help lead Australia to a fossil fuel-free future?

image.altText: Scott Morrison with Solomon Islands Prime Minister Manasseh Sogavare

props.synopsis: A strongly worded document from Tonga's Foreign Affairs Ministry gives insight into the Pacific nation's view of Australia and New Zealand's diplomatic efforts.

title.children: Leaked docs show Australia and NZ's 'condescending rhetoric' over China-Solomons security pact

image.altText: A white middle-aged man with dark hair wearing a maroon jacket leans over a railing in front a a river

props.synopsis: In the premiere episode of Creative Types, Trent Dalton, the bestselling author of Boy Swallows Universe,  shows host Virginia Trioli around the city that shaped him: Brisbane.

title.children: Trent Dalton could've processed his trauma through bourbon. He got creative instead

image.altText: A close up of a Bellinger River turtle face

props.synopsis: Nearly 100 captive-bred Bellinger River snapping turtles have been released into the wild, the biggest number yet for the breeding program after a virus nearly wiped them out in 2015.

title.children: These rare turtles are making a comeback after a mystery 'catastrophe' almost wiped them out
